{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515156"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:29:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:29:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12414"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.03,0.03,0.51,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77769"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63285"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1727"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77769"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents with a three-week history of right upper quadrant discomfort and fatigue. She is now experiencing a generalized itching, a dry mouth and eyes. Her medical history includes diabetes (for which she is on metformin), viral hepatitis and hypothyroidism which have been treated. Six months ago she had a course of amoxicillin for community acquired pneumonia. On examination her blood pressure is 135/89 mmHg, pulse 85/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Xanthelasma are noted on the eyelids and she has mild peripheral oedema is noted, liver span 17 cm, and shifting dullness is present. Some investigations are performed (image):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune hepatitis","Drug-related hepatotoxicity","Sarcoidosis","Primary biliary cholangitis","Liver cirrhosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms of the patient, association with Sjogren syndrome, xanthelasmas, deranged liver enzymes, raised cholesterol and presence high titre of anti-mitochondrial antibodies (AMA) are all consistent with the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary biliary cholangitis (PBC). \u003C/strong\u003EIt is a chronic disease of the liver effecting the small bile ducts, presumably autoimmune in nature, that leads to progressive cholestasis and often end-stage liver disease. It results from a slow, progressive destruction of the small bile ducts of the liver, causing bile and other toxins to build up in the liver, a condition called cholestasis. Further slow damage to the liver tissue can lead to scarring, fibrosis, and eventually cirrhosis. Furthermore, additional serologies for PBC are now coming used concluding GP210 SP 100 and M2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune hepatitis, \u003C/strong\u003Einflammation of liver due to body\u0027s own immune system usually remains asymptomatic initially. It can also present with similar symptoms as of PBC but is typically associated with positive autoantibodies such as antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and/or smooth muscle antibodies (SMA) in contrast to the anti-mitochondrial antibodies (AMA) present in PBC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-related hepatotoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E presents with fatigue, nausea and vomiting, loss of appetite, abdominal pain and tenderness, jaundice, dark urine, pale stools and itching. Most of the symptoms do not match in this case, she is currently only on metformin and had a recent course of amoxicillin both of which usually do not cause liver damage, moreover the positive AMA is diagnostic of PBC excluding this option. Drugs that can be hepatotoxic include methotrexate, statins, antifungals, NSAIDS, anticonvulsants, isoniazid and a few more.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by diffuse fibrosis and nodule formation caused by a variety of underlying diseases, including hepatitis, alcoholism, and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) etc. The history of viral hepatitis is a distractor but positive Anti-HBs and Anti-HBc indicate a past infection which has now resolved. A positive AMA does not imply presence of cirrhosis. This is suggestive of PBC as a potential aetiology but not necessarily severity of fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis \u003C/strong\u003Eof the Liver affects majority of patients with sarcoidosis (up to 70%). However, most of these patients rarely or never show symptoms in the liver. The patient would show multiorgan symptoms which is not the case here. It is not associated with AMA.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC), a chronic disease of the liver effecting the small bile ducts, presumably autoimmune in nature, and is AMA positive."],"references":["Pandit S, Samant H. Primary Biliary Cholangitis. [Updated 2023 Feb 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK459209/","Tanaka A, Ma X, Takahashi A, Vierling JM. Primary biliary cholangitis. Lancet. 2024 Sep 14;404(10457):1053-1066. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(24)01303-5. Epub 2024 Aug 28. PMID: 39216494. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39216494/","Trivella J, John BV, Levy C. Primary biliary cholangitis: Epidemiology, prognosis, and treatment. Hepatol Commun. 2023 Jun 2;7(6):e0179. doi: 10.1097/HC9.0000000000000179. PMID: 37267215; PMCID: PMC10241503. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37267215/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63285"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19189"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19189"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c88f955-82d2-43c9-8505-041376acf13a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c88f955-82d2-43c9-8505-041376acf13a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":418,"height":722}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63285"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T10:13:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T10:13:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4922"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77769"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","na